@course

id: book:atomic-habits-abcd
title: Atomic Habits
author: James Clear
description: How small daily actions compound into the person you become.
color: #4f46e5
genres: self-help, psychology
relevant_for: anyone, students, professionals

@segment
Small Changes, Big Results
SC

@package
The Two-Minute Morning
Free

@text
Most mornings start the same way.
You open your eyes and reach for something before you are fully awake.
Coffee, phone, or the same stretch you did yesterday.
You did not decide to do any of this today.
Your body moved before you had an opinion.

@text
Imagine you are standing in your kitchen at 6:47.
The light is still blue through the window.
You are holding a glass of water you do not remember pouring.
The kettle is starting to hum.
Your phone is face-down on the counter.
Last night you decided it would be there.
You did not have to convince yourself to do any of it.

@text
The water is boiling.
You reach for a book already open to the right page.
You read one paragraph. Just one.
Then you put it down, because the kettle is ready.
Tomorrow you will read one more paragraph.
You are not trying to finish the book this week.
You are trying to be someone who reads in the morning.

@text
Nothing in this morning was dramatic.
No alarm with a motivational quote, and no 60-minute routine from a podcast.
And yet, a few months from now, you will have finished a whole book.
You will have done it two minutes at a time.
The mornings shaped who you became.

@question
Why did the two-minute version of the habit work when longer attempts had not?

answer: Because two minutes is easy enough that you never have to convince yourself to start.
consequence: That is the intuitive answer, and it is right. The barrier to starting is what ends most habits. Making the start small removes the barrier.

answer: Because two minutes is long enough to make real progress.
consequence: Two minutes of reading is almost nothing in pages. But the habit is not about pages. It is about becoming someone who reads.

answer: Because short habits are more fun than long ones.
consequence: Short habits are often easier to enjoy. But enjoyment is not what keeps a habit going. What matters is whether starting feels easy every day.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A habit you can start without a fight is a habit you will still be doing next month. The size of the action matters less than the decision to begin.
hint: Think about what usually stops you before you even begin.

@text
The idea behind all of this has a name.
Researchers argue the smallest version of a habit is the one that lasts.
Not for what it does on a single day, but for what it adds up to.
Each tiny action nudges you closer to who you want to become.
They call this <c:g>identity-based habit change</c:g>.
You aim to become someone, not to reach a goal.

@true_false
A two-minute habit is too small to matter and will not produce real results.

true: True, two minutes is not enough.
consequence: Two minutes is not the point, it is the entry. Once you are reading daily, the sessions usually get longer. Even if they do not, you will still finish a book this year.

false: False, the small version is the point.
consequence: The habit grows by being continued, not by being ambitious on day one. The size of the commitment has little to do with the long-term result.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Small habits compound because they continue. Ambitious habits often produce one impressive week and then nothing.
hint: Ask which matters more, one perfect day or a year of imperfect ones.

@reflect
A habit that started as something small and became part of your identity: reading one page before bed.
An ambition that never survived its own first day because the first day asked for too much: a strict gym plan.
A small action you could add to tomorrow morning without needing to convince yourself: writing one sentence.
